    "review::.::holistic::initialization_coupling::sdk_module_mutable_singletons": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::initialization_coupling::sdk_module_mutable_singletons",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 2,
      "confidence": "medium",
      "summary": "sdk.ts has 3 module-level mutable variables creating implicit boot-order coupling",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "initialization_coupling",
        "related_files": [
          "src/lib/network/sdk.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "runtimeConfig (line 30), cryptoInitialized (line 36), logAgentName (line 37) are module-level let variables. loadMnemonic() mutates runtimeConfig as a side effect, meaning the order of loadMnemonic() vs getRpcUrl() calls matters. Multiple callers of loadMnemonic() in the same process would overwrite each other's config."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Consider encapsulating runtimeConfig, cryptoInitialized, and logAgentName into a SdkContext object created by a factory function, similar to how sdk-bridge.ts uses closure-scoped state. This would make the initialization dependency explicit and support multiple concurrent agent configs in the same process.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "ef8c6f11"
      },
      "status": "open",
